<p> 
</p>
<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Ninth session  
Agenda item 3 
</p>
<p><b>PROMOTION AND PROTECTION OF ALL HUMAN RIGHTS, 
CIVIL, POLITICAL, ECONOMIC, SOCIAL AND CULTURAL 
   RIGHTS, INCLUDING THE RIGHT TO DEVELOPMENT 
</b></p>
<p><b>Bolivia, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Chile, Colombia</b>*<b>, Congo</b>*<b>, 
Ecuador</b>*<b>, Egypt, Morocco</b>*<b>, Nicaragua, Panama</b>* <b>and 
 Uruguay:  draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>9/&#8230; United Nations guidelines for the appropriate use and 
conditions of alternative care for children 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council, 
</i></p>
<p> <i>Reaffirming</i> the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the Convention on the Rights 
of the Child, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling </i>and welcoming the international discussion launched in 2004 by the Committee 
on the Rights of the Child on the subject of children deprived of parental care, 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p>*  Non-member State of the Human Rights Council. </p>

<p>A/HRC/9/L.26 
page 2 
 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling</i> <i>also </i>and welcoming the initiative of UNICEF and the Committee on the Rights 
of the Child which, in 2005, devoted its annual day of general discussion to the issue of children 
deprived of parental care, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling further </i>and welcoming the recommendation of the Committee on the Rights of 
the Child that the international community should engage in the preparation of guidelines on 
alternative care, to be considered and adopted by the General Assembly, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling </i>and welcoming the intergovernmental meeting held in Brasilia, in August 2006, 
to analyse the preliminary version of the draft guidelines for the appropriate use and conditions 
of alternative care for children, based on the initial draft produced by experts and followed by the 
Committee on the Rights of the Child, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling</i> <i>also </i>and welcoming the broad consultative process held by the Council, which 
included joint statements by the Group of Friends, UNICEF and civil society representatives at 
its sixth session, resolution 7/29 adopted by consensus at its seventh session, and the high-level 
panel with broad participation held during the eighth session of the Council, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling</i> resolution 60/251 of the General Assembly, in which the Assembly established 
the Human Rights Council as the body responsible for promoting universal respect for the 
protection of all human rights and fundamental freedoms for all, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Reaffirms</i> the findings of the General Assembly in paragraph 16 of its 
resolution 62/141 and the importance of promoting appropriate parental care and family 
preservation where possible; 
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Also reaffirms</i> paragraph 19 of Council resolution 7/29, where it encourages the 
advancement of the draft United Nations guidelines for the appropriate use and conditions of 
alternative care for children; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Takes</i> <i>note</i> with appreciation of the draft United Nations guidelines for the 
appropriate use and conditions of alternative care for children; </p>

<p> A/HRC/9/L.26 
 page 3 
 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Requests</i> the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights to circulate, as 
soon as possible, the draft United Nations guidelines for the appropriate use and conditions of 
alternative care for children, with a view to give full knowledge of it to all members and 
observers of the Council; 
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Decides</i> to dedicate all its efforts with a view to the possible adoption of the draft 
United Nations guidelines for the appropriate use and conditions of alternative care for children 
by its tenth session. 
</p>
<p>----- </p>

